default4.1.
default 
defaultThere is a disjunction between the espoused “market led’ approach leading to freedom of choice for successful and satisfactory primary schools wanting to convert to an academy and the intercession at a number of levels by the DFE.
default&#xa0;
default4.2.
default 
defaultCreating an academy to i
defaultmprove standards is more likely to be a rapid, successful process when it is the result of common consent, rather than imposition.
default&#xa0;
default4.3.
default 
defaultSponsors have to plan to meet the demands of school improvement, financial probity and control, health and safety and good e
defaultstates management.  A clear commitment from the DfE to support them through their growth phase will significantly reduce risk and waste of public money and help establish successful academies.
default&#xa0;
default4.4.
default 
defaultExperienced sponsors are able to judge the potential fit for a
default school into their academy group by interrogating the wider context behind the top-level attainment data. A dialogue with DFE should be the norm.
default&#xa0;
default4.5.
default 
defaultFinancial incentives could be considered to schools on the threshold of satisfactory or requires improvement 
defaultwhen joining quality assured academy groups.  A more value for money approach to achieve the same outcome would be to streamline the process for approving sponsored and converter projects
default;
default where each month’s delay can 
defaultincur five figure lost revenues.
default&#xa0;
default4.6.
default 
defaultIt s
defaulthould be noted that the replacement of LACSEG by ESG in the new funding formula is now a major disincentive to primary schools. Running a primary academy group on anything less than 5-6% of GAG is unlikely to rapidly improve standards and invites the risk 
defaultof non-compliance on a range of requirements including sound estate management, governance and HR. Academy MAT’s that are mixed secondary and primary academies cross-subsidise.  An ESG of £150 per pupil equates to between 3-4% of the school’s budget.  This
default is no incentive for the good and outstanding primary schools to choose academy status and a reason for RI primary schools to resist the same.
